Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and attach handlers to all six events:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Created");
        window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Deactivated");
        window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Stopped");
        window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Resumed");
        window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Destroying");

        return window;
    }
}
```

**Typical sequences you'll see in the log:**

| Scenario | Events |
|---|---|
| Cold launch | `Created` â†’ `Activated` |
| App backgrounded | `Deactivated` â†’ `Stopped` |
| App resumed | `Resumed` â†’ `Activated` |
| Notification shade pulled | `Deactivated` only (no `Stopped`) |
| App closed | `Stopped` â†’ `Destroying` |

**Key gotchas:**

1. **`Resumed` does NOT fire on first launch** â€” the initial sequence is `Created` â†’ `Activated`.
2. **Android back button** can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`, so don't rely on `Stopped` alone for cleanup.
3. **Keep handlers fast** â€” Android enforces a ~5s ANR timeout; iOS has limited background time.

If you also need the raw **platform-native** callbacks (e.g., `OnPause`, `DidEnterBackground`), add `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` alongside these Window-level events.
